  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at preventing money laundering, including:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- International standards for combating money laundering\n- Adopted by over 180 countries\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Provides framework for international cooperation\n- Signed by 190 countries\n\n3. FATF Recommendations\n- Establish global standards for anti-money laundering policies\n- Require financial institutions to implement due diligence procedures\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision Guidelines\n- Set international banking standards\n- Includes recommendations for preventing money laundering\n\n5. Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n- International network of financial crime investigation units\n- Facilitates information sharing between countries\n\n6. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establish continent-wide regulations\n- Require strict reporting and monitoring of financial transactions\n\nMost countries have national laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
